The crude stratifications and linearly aligned lapilli layers in the poorly sorted matrix suggest that the inverse to normally graded
volcaniclastic gravelly sandstones were deposited by hyperconcentrated flows (Pierson, 2005; Scott, 1988; Smith, 1986; Smith & Lowe, 1991; Sohn, Rhee, & Kim, 1999). The stacking of inversely graded layers in the lower part showing crude planar stratifications was formed by traction carpets in highly concentrated lower part of the hyperconcentrated flows (Pierson, 2005; Sohn, 1997; Todd, 1989). The upward increase in thickness of the layers and size of constituent clasts reflects a gradual increase in the sedimentation rate and competence of the flows. The poorly sorted and coarse‐grained upper part is suggestive of direct accumulation of sediments with no tractional component (Lowe, 1982, 1988; Sumner, Amy, & Talling, 2008). However, the linear alignments of lapilli layers are indicative of temporal changes in turbulence intensity or shear velocity over a depositional boundary. Transversely aligned, lithic blocks are interpreted to have rolled onto the beds and have been trapped by the aggrading depositional boundary (Cronin, Neall, Lecointre, & Palmer, 1997;
Pierson, 2005). The normal grading in the uppermost part with planar or low‐angle cross‐stratifications represents the waning of parental flows with a decrease in sedimentation rate over the depositional boundary.
